  "text": "## Kubernetes Lease-Based Leader Election\n\nKubernetes implements leader election using a **lease-based approach** with periodic renewal, as seen in the client-go library and Kubernetes control plane controllers.\n\n### Architecture\nThe implementation consists of three layers:\n\n1. **Resource Lock Layer** (`staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection/resourcelock/`): Abstracts the storage backend for leader election records. The `Interface` defines Get/Create/Update operations, with `LeaseLock` implementing these using the Kubernetes Lease API (coordination.k8s.io/v1). A `LeaderElectionRecord` is stored in the Lease spec, containing HolderIdentity, AcquireTime, RenewTime, LeaseDurationSeconds, and LeaderTransitions.\n\n2. **Leader Elector Layer** (`staging/src/k8s.io/client-go/tools/leaderelection/leaderelection.go`): The main `LeaderElector` orchestrates the election process. The `Run()` method starts the election loop, calling `acquire()` to gain leadership and `renew()` to maintain it. The `tryAcquireOrRenew()` function implements a fast-path for incumbents (checking locally cached lease validity) and a slow-path for challengers (fetching from API server). Leadership changes trigger `OnStartedLeading`/`OnStoppedLeading` callbacks.\n\n3. **Controller Layer** (`pkg/controlplane/controller/leaderelection/`): Kubernetes components integrate leader election with controller logic. The `leaderelection_controller.go` coordinates leader election for components, while `leasecandidate.go` implements coordinated leader election with version-based candidate promotion (ALPHA feature).\n\n### Failover and Re-election Mechanism\n- **Lease Duration**: The `LeaseDuration` (typically 15s) defines how long a non-leader must wait before attempting to take over after the incumbent's last renewal.\n- **Renewal**: The leader continuously calls `renew()`, which polls every `RetryPeriod` (typically 2s) until `RenewDeadline` (typically 10s).\n- **Failover**: When the incumbent crashes or fails to renew, the lease naturally expires. Any non-leader can then call `tryAcquireOrRenew()` to acquire the lease by updating it with their identity.\n- **Clock Tolerance**: The implementation uses local timestamps only, tolerating arbitrary clock skew by waiting for RenewDeadline periods.\n- **Transitions**: `LeaderTransitions` counter tracks leadership changes for monitoring.\n\n---\n\n## etcd Raft-Based Leader Election\n\netcd implements leader election using the **Raft consensus algorithm** for internal cluster leadership, complemented by a client-facing election API based on leases.\n\n### Internal Raft-Based Architecture\n\nThe Raft layer (`server/etcdserver/raft.go`, `server/etcdserver/server.go`) manages cluster leader election:\n\n1. **Raft Node** (`raftNode`): Runs the Raft state machine in a dedicated goroutine. The `start()` method monitors `r.Ready()` channels, which emit raft.Ready structs containing state changes, committed entries, and messages.\n\n2. **Leader State Tracking**: When Raft detects a leader change via `rd.SoftState.Lead`, the `raftReadyHandler` callbacks update the EtcdServer:\n   - `updateLead()` via `setLead()` atomically stores the new leader ID\n   - `updateLeadership()` handles role-specific logic: demoting lessor and pausing compactor on followers, resuming them on leaders\n   - `leaderChanged.Notify()` signals leader changes\n\n3. **Failover Mechanism**: Raft automatically holds elections when:\n   - Followers don't receive heartbeats (within `heartbeat` interval)\n   - Candidates increment their term and send RequestVote RPCs\n   - The first node to gain a majority becomes leader\n   - This is detected via `rd.RaftState == raft.StateLeader`\n\n### Client-Facing Election API\n\netcd exposes a higher-level election API for applications:\n\n1. **Session Layer** (`client/v3/concurrency/session.go`): Creates a lease-backed session with automatic keep-alive. Sessions use `client.KeepAlive()` to maintain liveness.\n\n2. **Election Primitives** (`client/v3/concurrency/election.go`):\n   - `Campaign(ctx, val)`: Atomically creates a key at `keyPrefix/{leaseID}` with a compare-and-swap transaction. If already created, waits for lower-revision keys to be deleted via `waitDeletes()`, implementing a queue-based election.\n   - `Proclaim(ctx, val)`: Updates the value without re-election, conditional on key revision matching.\n   - `Resign(ctx)`: Deletes the leader key, triggering the next candidate.\n   - `Leader(ctx)`: Queries the current leader (first key by creation revision).\n   - `Observe(ctx)`: Streams leader changes via watching and comparing create revisions.\n\n3. **Server-Side gRPC API** (`server/etcdserver/api/v3election/election.go`): The `electionServer` adapts protobuf messages to the concurrency election primitives, exposing Campaign, Proclaim, Resign, Leader, and Observe operations.\n\n### Failover and Re-election in etcd\n\n**At the Raft layer**: Failover is automatic via Raft timeouts:\n- If the leader becomes unavailable, followers timeout and become candidates\n- Candidates send RequestVote to peers; the first to win a majority becomes leader\n- The Raft term counter ensures safety: stale leaders are rejected\n- Detected via `rd.SoftState.Lead` transitioning to `raft.None` and back\n\n**At the application layer**: Election re-campaigns when:\n- The lease expires (session keep-alive fails)\n- The leader explicitly resigns\n- Candidates wait for all higher-revision keys to be deleted before becoming leader\n\n### Comparison\n\n**Kubernetes**: Uses optimistic lease renewal with periodic polling. Simple, stateless, but requires API server availability and tolerates clock skew.\n\n**etcd**: Uses Raft for automatic, byzantine-fault-tolerant cluster consensus. More complex but ensures strong consistency and automatic failover without external coordination. The client election API layered on top provides similar semantics to Kubernetes but with stronger guarantees.\n"
